segments.text: You tell me, you guide me, what you need me to say.
One of the things I was interested in was using electrophoretic techniques for purifying proteans.
Fortunately, he was the person to talk to, and I didn't know that at the time.
I just, you know, I would be in the hall or see him in the hall, and he'd be, he quite often visited with his students, his own students, as well as other faculty.
And I don't know, maybe he spent more time for his students than other people, because he was, I believe he was department head at the time.
I think so.
But he was very frequently in the hall, and so I had the occasion to visit with him on several occasions on, you know, using, applying electrophoretic techniques.
Now you had, so you're taking a full load.
Yes.
But you're also teaching, working full time.
Well, that's part of the responsibility.
But yeah, yeah, oh yeah.
And when would those instructional duties begin for you?
Those would be at least two times a week, two full afternoons a week.
You're saying four hours?
Mm-hmm.
And how much preparation time did each lab session require for you all?
Well, quite often we'd prepare about an hour or so before the exam.
I mean, not before the exam, before the exam.

and fortunately you see if we had not known pretty well if we hadn't had the laboratory experience that we had had that would have been chaos that would have been but we knew pretty well I mean we need this we need this blood auger we need this kind of media we need this kind of media and we're going to be talking about E. coli today so we don't need the blood auger but we need some EMB and we need the nutrient auger and we're going to need these various biochemicals

and we had even at that time we had a pretty good support staff so we could say look we're going to need before this afternoon or before before next Thursday afternoon we're going to need this for this many students and that's about you know and how would you describe the facilities in veterinary medicine at that time in comparison now uh
See, I had been accustomed to state of the art, I mean, with the Army, state of the art laboratory facilities.
And they were very good facilities.
They stacked up very well with that.

They stacked up much better than, for example, the facilities at the University of Texas, the microbiology facilities at the University of Texas, and certainly better than the facilities that they had at Southwest Texas.
They were not comparable to what the Army had because, you know, they had an unlimited budget.
But they, somebody, and I guess it was Leland, had the foresight to hire these ladies from Caldwell and the surrounding community who were committed to wanting to do a good job
And they generally did exactly as they were told.
And I mean, you know, they followed instructions very well.
And what was their task?
Making media and helping in the preparation, you know, setting up things for the labs and so forth.
Now during your first semesters, first year or so, do you remember any unusual goof ups for you or anybody else where you all learned by experience or something went wrong?
Something didn't work?
Oh, I'm trying to think of some.
Yeah, there were several.
Well, misidentifying, I mean, using some things for the wrong thing.
Yeah, there's a group of organisms called Clostridia.

that produce a lot of gas and if you if you put in a lot of sugar in the media and you try to stopper the media those you inoculate the media and at various times during the day those you shouldn't be using stoppered media to begin with with Clostridia and that sort of thing
But we got the media mixed up, and during the class you'd see these stoppers popping off because of the amount of gas that was being produced by those things.
Oh, I'm hard-pressed to think of any...
Nothing exploded, nothing caught fire?
Well, yes, as a matter of fact, we almost had a disaster at one time.

now you can't use things like ether you know very readily but another individual I don't know that I should mention his name because he later became a department head in another department but he was a graduate student at that time too and he was working he was in another department but he was working in our area and he's working with ether
And ether has a tendency, you know, it's heavier than air so it tends to go along the floor and the vapors go along the floor.
And one of these individuals, Paul Youngerman, was a heavy smoker and of course at that time you could smoke anywhere.
And he was smoking one time and this individual who
who was working with the ether, he was trying to do some lipid extraction.
At that time you used ether to extract lipids.
And so he was trying to extract some things and he wasn't using a fume hood.
Fume hoods were rarely used at that time too.
So the ether vapors went along and here was Paul Youngerman and he flipped off some ashes on the floor.
Fortunately, that's all it did, but it could have caused a very serious problem.
How much did you see in your first semesters of the Dean of Veterinary Medicine?
Didn't see him at all.
He didn't come around to instruct you?
No, I'll tell you, no, he didn't.
When did you first meet him?
Actually, Al Price was the dean that was there when I was there as a graduate student.

I used to, I was kind of a glutton for punishment, I guess, because I was kind of interested in, I didn't want to take a course in histology, but I was kind of interested in the subject because I, frankly, had plans.
After I kind of got the
I had plans ultimately of going back after getting my Ph.D. to go back to medical school.
I never did do that, but I sort of had plans to.
But I was kind of interested in histology, and that was Al Price's field.
He was another one of those stellar individuals.
There are several people who probably weren't nationally known or internationally known, but I think that they're, I have had lectures.
As an undergraduate at the University of Texas, I had taken classes with a painter whom perhaps you know.
Theophilus.
Theophilus, right.
He was a stellar, he was an outstanding lecturer.
And so, my point of reference is that there were a number of people like this that I had the good fortune to know and participate in their classes.
And while Al and some of the others that I'm gonna mention in just a moment didn't have the national and international name, they were very good.
very good people too, Al Price, R.D.
Turk, who was a parasitologist.
A character from the word go, sort of like Paul Youngerman.
Paul Youngerman was a character too.
Archie Flowers was a pretty good man too.
And then I'd put Mac Prescott in that same league.
Did you ever have a course with Dean Price?
No, I didn't.
He let me set in on his course, and he was very good at it.
I mean, very good lecturer.
So he was teaching, still teaching course while he was leaving?
Sure.
Oh, you bet.
You bet.
Yeah.
Now, he was nicknamed a long time before you got here as Slick Al.
That's right.
And I presume that meant that when he finished the product,
It was well polished.
Well, he was kind of a politician himself.
He had a good way with words.
But it was not meant that he was going to put something off on somebody.
No, that's true.
He was very...
very decisive, very forceful.
You know, he explained when he, and he was kind of strict on a code of conduct, too.
Oh, what was the code of conduct?
Well, you were to wear ties at all times.
You were to wear, not to wear boots.
you were to have a completely professional demeanor, students and faculty.
And in fact, I believe his title was Assistant Dean McMurray.
Did you know him or know of him?
He was an individual that tried to buck, maybe I shouldn't be, don't use, I mean, use your own discretion.

McMurray was the kind of individual that he really kind of he kind of wanted to be Dean himself but he didn't have the he didn't really didn't have the hoot spot to be but he kind of bucked Al quite a bit Al was always very neatly dressed and he spoke very well he I doubt that I don't know where I don't imagine Al ever said damn or anything like that he was very
But McMurray almost got fired one time because he started wearing boots.
He did the other things, you know.
He wore jackets and that sort of thing, but he wanted to wear boots.
And I think it almost fired him over that incident.
Because he was very, Al was very.
How long was it after you got here that you decided very definitely that you would get a PhD here whether you went to medical school or not?
How long did it take you to make that decision?
I was pretty well, financially, I was doing better than I'd ever done in my life as a student.
So, I mean, I, you know, we,
I grew up very poor, Carol and I both were very poor.
So we felt, I mean, we were very comfortable even as students here, but Carol was still working pretty hard too.
Let's see, your question was, how long did it take me to decide?
I decided almost right away that that's what I wanted to do, is get a PhD.
Now, my dad asked me, son, you're getting a PhD in what?
And I said, veterinary microbiology.
I thought you was gonna be a doctor.
Well, I'm not sure.
Well, we sure thought you were gonna be a doctor, a PhD in what again?
I said, veterinary microbiology.
Are you gonna be a veterinarian?
I don't think so, Dan.
Well, what the hell does a veterinary microbiologist do if he's not a veterinarian?
I had a conversation very much like that too.
What can you do with a degree in history?
What can you make?
A direct answer to your question.
I knew right away that that's what I wanted to do.
I was working on a problem that I was interested in.
I was in an environment that was, to me, very stimulating.
And how long did it take you to identify what you were going to do as your research topic?
After the first semester.
Okay, and describe it.
Okay, yeah, well, yeah, yeah, it's, in fact, it's something that I, the subject is equine infectious anemia.
Okay, equine infectious anemia.
I knew nothing, know nothing about horses.
Mm-hmm.
Infectious anemia is a disease that at that time was ravaging the racehorses of the country.
Well, that didn't bother me.
I mean, I wasn't high on, right?
But it was a problem that they didn't really know what the etiology was.
They weren't real sure whether it was a virus or whether it was a PPLO-like, they called them PPLO-like organisms at that time, or whether it was a toxin.
And so this was really a challenge to me that I really thought, I felt like it was, and the guy that I worked with felt like that it was a virus.
And I had happened to have had some experience in cell culture methodology.
You've gotta have grow, in order to cultivate and study viruses, you've gotta have cell culture systems.
So I knew right away then that that's,
Did someone suggest it to you, or did you come up with the idea?
No, no one suggested it to me, but a fellow by the name of Wayne Moore, I don't know if you have heard of him or know of him, knew of him or anything.
Wayne was one of these guys, real bright guys, but he was on the faculty.
But he was pursuing a number of,

disease animal disease problems and and one of them was equine infectious anemia and I told him that I asked you know I got to quizzing him about that about that situation he said you know it's a strange thing Don said we've got this old Appaloosa's horse over here that has never shown any signs of it
But if we take blood out of that horse and inject it into another horse, the horse will come down with the disease 14 days later.
The unique thing about that disease, still kind of an interesting disease, the unique thing about that disease is that the affected animal goes through a very structured cyclical pattern.
Each 14 days they go into fever and then they'll clear up and be normal and then they'll go into this.
Well, so I was intrigued by the idea of being able to.
Who ended up being your chairman?
Leland.
Leland Grumbles.
Mm-hm.
Although Wayne directed my work.
And you all had agreed upon this as your topic within the first year?
Yeah.
Mm-hm.

right now meanwhile let's go to personal life describe you and wife and Donald a youngster describe y'all getting a place to live oh listen yeah well I was when we how did you find a place well again this is one this is personal I mean this is the kind of story that may not be of any interest to you but it's I have been lucky uh in a number of ways throughout my life and we um

You know, after I decided to come here, after we had decided to come here, Carol and I had decided to come here, we didn't know for sure where we were gonna live because married student housing was full at that time.
I had decided I was gonna come here, but I didn't know where I was gonna live and knew nothing about, and really, housing was kinda scarce even at that time.
And again, I happened to be in the post office.
there in the college station where the university post office is still there.
Northgate.
Northgate, right.
And there's a fellow there by the name of Sam B.
Pate.
He's still around.
And I was talking with Gordon, I believe, or somebody else in the post office, and he overheard me saying this, talking about the plight that I was in, and
And he said, young man, I might can help you out with that situation.
So we, again, to make a long story short, we moved out there.
He had a place that was out north of Bryan on Highway 21, sort of in the country, and just perfect.
Carol just loved that place.
And so we moved there and we stayed there for the duration of my graduate studies.
Do you remember what the rent was?
I think it was $50 a month or something like that.
Just really, hardly anything.
But the Pates were just marvelous people.
They treated us like we were their children.
And in fact, Donald, my oldest son, was a child at that time, and then we were expecting a second child.
And the house that we lived in, it was just a one-bedroom house, a small place that Mr.
Pate, Sam B.
Pate, had built for his son and wife to live while they were going to school.
And so it was just ideal for us.
And we told him that we was going to have to move.
And he said, look, I'll be happy to sell that house to you.
And I said, well, Mr.
Pate, I just can't afford it.
He said...
You won't believe how much I said, well, really, and the real reason why we couldn't do that was because our flat family was growing, so we moved away.
Well, the paint place, CMB Paint, about two years after we moved off of the place.
Now, see, he was offering to sell it to us.
About two years after we moved off the place.
Right.
Oil was discovered.
Oil was discovered and Mr.
Pate, that property was all worth a lot of money.
So we moved over on Villa Maria and there we had kiddos and John and then ultimately moved here.
Did you buy a house or rent?
No, we bought a house.
Bought a house.
Bought a house.
what was it like for the two of you and your youngster to become part of the community?
How did you all make friends?
Well, the Pates were just marvelous people.
As I say, we had been so lucky throughout all of our, I mean, you know, we've, it's just, I don't know, we've just been real lucky with just about everything.
into the Bryan area, for a long time we were recognized as students.
And students were sort of, I mean, particularly the merchants.
The students, the air base had just closed.
And so there was a lot of negative feelings about the air base personnel and a lot of negative feelings about the student personnel.

it it really didn't impact us all that much except that people weren't as friendly as we thought they should be but if you were part of the old Bryan community I mean there was a vast difference it's it's kind of strange how a community seems like a community develops a personality like a person individual you know like an individual had a community has a personality
But once we became part of the, you know, recognized as part of the community, this has always been just the friendliest community.
And the same is true here in College Station.
Now, we became acquainted with y'all, of course, at church.
Now, did y'all come to the First Presbyterian Church in Bryan soon after you arrived?
Well, not too long.
No, we were here about a year before we...
We became members of the First Presbyterian Church.
We were looking around for churches.
Neither one of us had been very active in church prior to that time.
We were looking for a church in which our kiddos could be comfortable and grow up, Donald and John.
And we felt like that if we were going to do that, we... Well, the First Presbyterian Church, we attended...
I grew up in the Church of Christ, I might add.
And so we went to the Church of Christ and of course that was, now don't tell JD this because, erase this part, don't ever show this to JD, because he is Church of Christ.
But Hellfire and Brimstone and all that kind of stuff, no musical accompaniment, you know the story.
Anyway, we became members of the, we explored the,
First Presbyterian Church, number one, because their music program, and number two, because it looked like they were going to have a pretty good youth program.
Now, the minister at the time y'all came, was it Dick Thomas?
Dick Thomas, Dick Thomas.
And so we became acquainted first with the Porterfields, Peg and Clyde Porterfield, and then later with the Heilers.
And so the three of us,
I forgot whether it's Clyde and Peg or whether it was the Hilers invited us to become, they asked us if we wanted to be, because we had a pretty good background in youth care and that sort of thing.

Dick came out to see us one night, he said, well Don and Carol, we'd love to have you as members, we'd love to have you as youth advisors, but if you're gonna be youth advisors, you've got to be members of this church.
And so we, and I enjoyed the music.
I was very impressed with the music program there.
So we then became members of the church and became fairly active in the church.
Now, how long before you got into the choir was that?
Oh, almost immediately.
Oh, okay.
Because I went by the choir one night.
We were living not too far from there on Villa Maria.
And I went by the choir one night and I,

just just walked in you know I didn't I hadn't said I was coming or talked to any of them and I said I just walked in as they were beginning to rehearse and I said to I was wondering I've been impressed with the choir and I was wondering if I could be a member of it and it just chaos when I you know as I walked in and so that's just sort of a spontaneous thing Frank Coulter was the director.
Frank Coulter was the director and who was the organist then?
the lady whose husband was an entomologist.
I can't think either right now.
But Fern Hammond.
Fern Hammond, yes.
And the congregation, the worship services were held in what is now the recreation, the Fellowship Hall.
No, it had just, I mean... Oh, it just moved to the...
It had just moved.
I mean, within...
Within a month or so after we became, you know, after we joined there.
And it just moved over there.
All right.
Now let's go back to you.
How long in your laboratory instructor duties were those spring and fall, or was it 12 months of the year that you had labs to teach?
No, it was spring and fall.
And, in fact, I just did that for one year.
Okay.
And then what did you do?
After that I got involved in research.
You didn't have a faculty appointment that second year?
No, I didn't have a faculty appointment until I finished.
So you were then on someone's research budget?
On the research budget, no, I was on what was referred to as a Gant.
Okay, all right.
I don't know, I guess they still use that terminology.
And whose project were you working on?
Actually, Wayne Moore's.

as well as I got to do a lot of interesting you know it was just the world was just really exciting to me I could I became a workaholic and I guess I maintained those those characteristics I spent a lot of time another person I don't know if you knew him or know of him his name was he's an electron microscopist Hugh Grant Whitehouse he
was a strange mix.
He was apparently a very bright individual.
He had been with the Manhattan Project during the Second World War.
But he was director of the electron microscopy center.
And because I had the theory that we were dealing, see the etiology of the disease wasn't truly known at that time.
And so I was really anxious to try to get some specimens and look at them under the electron microscope.
So I cultivated his, tried to cultivate his, and did cultivate his friendship to use the electron microscope.
And so I spent between the time of, I mean, I spent most of my, the remaining years, I mean, I spent one year in the teaching, sort of in the instructional mode.
Well, part of my duties too were,
There was a glitch in funding for one semester, but I mean, I never suffered from that.
But the department had the responsibility at that time for salmonella pallorum testing of turkeys and chickens and that sort of thing, which meant that they would bring in

birds from various flocks and they had to be cultured they had to be tested serologically and then they had to be cultured for the presence of those particular agents and so part of my responsibility was to was to culture for those but you know do that testing and much of that work was done by by Gordon and myself and Gordon had been doing that
all the time and then they got overwhelmed with it and there was a glitch in my funding and so they just shifted me over to that project for about, you know, for a semester or so.
Right, so after that first year when you were teaching and had laboratory responsibilities, then you were a full-time researcher.
That's correct.
And so you're there eight to ten hours a day.
More.
Okay, five days a week or six?
Well, officially five days a week, but in actuality I was there seven days a week because I was really interested in what I was trying to do.
And what kind of laboratory facility were you provided?
Well, I had two or three homes in which I could work.
One of them was out in what is now identified as Veterinary Research Park.
There were some old buildings out there, and I could say, Dr. Moore, I need a column, and I need to set this column up, and I need this electrophoretic equipment.
You ready?
Get it.

And so we essentially set up a laboratory for protean purification, cell culture, and that sort of thing, which again was sort of, you know, it was state of the art, but it was sort of, you know, we sort of put it together.
And so what I would be doing would be developing cell cultures.
First, I was picking up, as horses were...
